snippet.textDisplay:
I just want to say thank you for doing what you do. A week ago, you would've caught me saying all sorts of negative things regarding the boss design in Elden Ring, but now I've come to the conclusion that perhaps it's simply just me and the mentality I've set for this game the first time going through and stuck with it for the rest of my time ingame. I knew I had to be mistaken on something a little after finishing the DLC, as I watched LMSH no-hit Messmer. Now, I never thought I'd manage a no-hit to any boss, however, I decided after watching that and reminding myself about the many challenge players that exist within game, to undertake some exploration with my perspective. I went to yours and another's video regarding the boss designs, and decided to undertake a challenge for myself using the advice present in those videos; I took up a standard longsword, namely the Lordsworn's for its crit, and I fought the bosses. When I've gotten to Godrick... I died; I died a lot. Too many times. However, I managed to learn the boss by stepping outside of my mentality and I've learned him for the first time. Only having to get hit once while always being beside him. My proudest lesson was learning his ground aoe attack, of which I figured out that I can punish him my using a jump r1 attack compared to a jump r2 attack while simultaneously jumping and still avoiding the attack consistently. It may not be much for some players, since Godrick is not complex like the others, but I found myself enjoying a mediocre boss while also learning to be patient with the game.

That being said, I'm still going through the game with the longsword, but I've enjoyed every bit of it thus far, and I thank you for proving that my perspective was wrong.

snippet.textDisplay:
ik im late to this but still. it should be rather obvious of the difference between the two players. the guy who has only completed the game once would most likely only know of a few select locations from memmory or exploring through his 1st run in which he knows where some hidden or secret items are along with the standard stuff that comes alongside the story. not only that, he would have very little experience against the bosses and wouldnt likely know how to be able to easily deal with every single one of them.

as for the 2k hours guy. its like playing the elder scrolls V skyrim for example for that long. uve searched the map enough for many hidden items, have methods in which to obtain some usually hard to get items, know specific dialogue options to obtain free gear or get different or hidden items and which locations are best to go to early on for a really good start or a really good item. 

Its like saying that who would win against an experienced player who knows how to make potions in skyrim versus a new player who hasnt touched the game before nor has any knowledge of the game and who can complete the game 1st is the winner.
